n response to changes in the level of activity, ensuring that the budget remains relevant and accurate.", "\"ZERO-BASED BUDGETING\":Zero-Based Budgeting is a method where the budget is prepared from scratch, with all expenses needing justification for each new period. Each new budget is started from a 'zero base,' and every function within an organization is analyzed for its needs and costs. This approach helps in cost control and efficiency but is more time-consuming. This quiz tests knowledge of Zero-Based Budgeting, a method where all activities are re-evaluated each time a budget is formulated.", "\"BEYOND BUDGETING\":\"This quiz tests knowledge of Beyond Budgeting, which involves the use of stretch goals and devolution of resource decisions to front-line teams.\"", "\"BUDGETED PRODUCTION COST\":\"This quiz involves calculating the budgeted total production cost for Jessie Co, given estimates of variable and fixed costs at different production levels.\"", "\"FLEXED BUDGET STATEMENTS\":\"The quiz on flexed budgets involves identifying correct statements about flexed budgets, including their preparation at expected activity levels, use for identifying variances due to different activity levels, and reliance on original budget assumptions.\"", "\"STANDARD COSTING USE\":\"The quiz on standard costing use involves identifying activities for which standard costing would not be used, such as determining expenses for reporting to shareholders.\"", "\"MATERIALS VARIANCE\":\"The quiz on materials variance involves calculating the total materials variance using a flexed budget approach, given budgeted and actual levels of activity and costs.\"", "\"FIXED OVERHEAD EXPENDITURE\":\"The quiz on fixed overhead expenditure involves calculating the actual fixed overhead expenditure given a variance and budgeted overhead.\"", "\"SALES VOLUME VARIANCE QUIZ\":\"This quiz involves calculating the sales volume variance using marginal costing principles. Darwin Co budgeted to sell 25,000 units at a budgeted selling price of $20 per unit, with a budgeted contribution of $12 per unit. The actual sales were 26,500 units, resulting in a sales volume variance of $18,000 favorable.\"", "\"ADVERSE MATERIALS USAGE VARIANCE QUIZ\":\"This quiz asks which of the following is unlikely to be an explanation for an adverse materials usage variance. The options are stricter quality control, bulk discount, cheaper material being purchased, and change in mix of materials. The correct answer is bulk discount.\"", "\"SALES MIX VARIANCE QUIZ\":\"This quiz involves calculating the sales mix variance for three products (X, Y, Z) with given budgeted and actual sales data. The correct answer is $200 favorable.\"", "\"MATERIALS MIX VARIANCE QUIZ\":\"This quiz involves calculating the materials mix variance for a process with a standard mix and actual materials used. The correct answer is $2,400 adverse.\"", "\"MATERIALS YIELD VARIANCE QUIZ\":\"This quiz involves calculating the materials yield variance for a standard cost of a 10-liter tin of metal paint. The standard cost includes 5 liters of A at $6 per liter, 3 liters of B at $4 per liter, and 2 liters of C at $9 per liter. During the period, 1,020 tins were produced requiring 5,400 liters of A and 3,200 liters of B.\"", "\"MONITORING QUALITY WITH NFPIS\":\"This quiz focuses on identifying the most suitable non-financial performance indicator (NFPI) for monitoring quality, with options including throughput volume, new customers, customer complaints, and transactions per customer.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}